===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm}}, from {{etyl|ang}} {{term|bæþ||bath|lang=ang}}, from {{proto|Germanic|baþan|bath|lang=en}}, from {{proto|Indo-European|bhe-|to warm|lang=en}}. Cognate with {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|bad||bath|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|Bad||bath|lang=de}}, {{etyl|da|-}} {{term|bad||bath|lang=da}}, {{etyl|is|-}} {{term|bað||bath|lang=is}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|bähen||to foment|lang=de}}. More at {{l|en|beath}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# A [[tub]] or [[pool]] which is used for [[bathing]]: [[bathtub]].
# A [[room]] or [[area]] where [[bathing]] occurs: [[bathroom]].
# The act of [[bathing]].
# A [[substance]] or [[preparation]] into which something is [[immersed]].
#* {{quote-book|year=1879 |title=The Telephone, the Microphone and the Phonograph
|author=Th Du Moncel |page=166 |publisher=Harper
|passage=He takes the prepared charcoal used by artists, brings it to a white heat, and suddenly plunges it in a '''bath''' of mercury, of which the globules instantly penetrate the pores of charcoal, and may be said to metallize it.}}

=====Usage notes=====
Sense 3. is usually ''to '''take''' ''(US)'' or '''have''' ''(UK, Aus)'' a bath.'' See also [[Appendix:Collocations of do, have, make, and take]]

